Rating: 2
I grilled 1" steaks on a medium-high barbecue, 5 minutes to a side. The pepper rub is tasty. However, the addition of the black butter at the end made the final result quite oily, what with the olive oil already added in the rub. I suggest skipping the black butter and serving lemon wedges to squeeze on the steaks, as a nice complement to the oil & pepper rub.

Rating: 3
The spice rub makes a crust that really works well with medium-rare salmon's creaminess. Just use a heavy-bottomed pan because the rub wants to burn really bad. The blackened butter is okay, but you could really use almost any light sauce, or even a lemon squeeze. The spice rub is what matters.

Rating: 4
This dish is so easy to make. I cook this for my Fiance, who does not like fish, but she loves this dish. Even if you cannot cook, this dish is to easy to mess up on.

Rating: 4
Because of the excellent reviews of this recipe, I decided to adapt it for a large filet of salmon. I put a piece of aluminum foil in the bottom of a broiler pan, sprayed it with oil and placed the salmon diagonally in the pan, skin side down. Then I spread the paste onto the top of the filet and broiled it six inches below medium heat for fifteen minutes. The result was beyond compare! I served it with steamed spinach with a lemon wedge and a baked potato for a simple family dinner. Everyone gave the salmon four stars!

